goterms.name: angioblast cell migration
goterms.description: The orderly movement of angioblasts, cells involved in blood vessel morphogenesis.

goterms.name: angiogenesis
goterms.description: Blood vessel formation when new vessels emerge from the proliferation of pre-existing blood vessels.

goterms.name: angiogenesis involved in coronary vascular morphogenesis
goterms.description: Blood vessel formation in the heart when new vessels emerge from the proliferation of pre-existing blood vessels.

goterms.name: cell migration involved in coronary angiogenesis
goterms.description: The orderly movement of a cell from one site to another that will contribute to the formation of new blood vessels in the heart from pre-existing blood vessels.

goterms.name: angiogenesis involved in wound healing
goterms.description: Blood vessel formation when new vessels emerge from the proliferation of pre-existing blood vessels and contribute to the series of events that restore integrity to a damaged tissue, following an injury.

goterms.name: branching involved in blood vessel morphogenesis
goterms.description: The process of coordinated growth and sprouting of blood vessels giving rise to the organized vascular system.

goterms.name: positive regulation of blood vessel branching
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of blood vessel branching.

goterms.name: negative regulation of vessel branching
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of blood vessel branching.

goterms.name: intussusceptive angiogenesis
goterms.description: The formation of new blood vessels as a result of the insertion and extension of lumenal tissue pillars.

goterms.name: blood vessel endothelial cell migration involved in intussusceptive angiogenesis
goterms.description: The orderly movement of endothelial cells into the extracellular matrix in order to form new blood vessels during intussusceptive angiogenesis.

goterms.name: negative regulation of angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of angiogenesis.

goterms.name: positive regulation of angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases angiogenesis.

goterms.name: sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: The extension of new blood vessels from existing vessels into avascular tissues, this process includes the specialization of endothelial cells into leading tip and stalk cells, proliferation and migration of the endothelial cells and cell adhesion resulting in angiogenic sprout fusion or lumen formation.

goterms.name: negative regulation of sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: positive regulation of sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: angiogenic sprout fusion
goterms.description: The connection of an angiogenic sprout to another vessel or sprout during the formation of vascular networks by sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: cell adhesion involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: The attachment of a cell, either to another cell or to an underlying substrate such as the extracellular matrix, via cell adhesion molecules that contributes to the formation of a blood vessel network.

goterms.name: negative regulation of cell adhesion involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cell adhesion involved in sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: positive regulation of cell adhesion involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cell adhesion involved in sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: blood vessel endothelial cell proliferation involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: The multiplication or reproduction of blood vessel endothelial cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population contributing to sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: negative regulation of blood vessel endothelial cell proliferation involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of blood vessel endothelial cell proliferation involved in sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: positive regulation of blood vessel endothelial cell proliferation involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of blood vessel endothelial cell proliferation involved in sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: The orderly movement of endothelial cells into the extracellular matrix in order to form new blood vessels involved in sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: negative regulation of cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis. Cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis is the orderly movement of endothelial cells into the extracellular matrix in order to form new blood vessels contributing to the process of sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: positive regulation of cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis. Cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis is the orderly movement of endothelial cells into the extracellular matrix in order to form new blood vessels contributing to the process of sprouting angiogenesis.

goterms.name: endothelial stalk cell fate specification
goterms.description: The process involved in the specification of identity of an endothelial stalk cell. Once specification has taken place, a cell will be committed to differentiate down a specific pathway if left in its normal environment. An endothelial stalk cell is a specialized endothelial cell which follows behind the tip cell of an angiogenic sprout.

goterms.name: endothelial tip cell fate specification
goterms.description: The process involved in the specification of identity of an endothelial tip cell. Once specification has taken place, a cell will be committed to differentiate down a specific pathway if left in its normal environment. An endothelial tip cell is a specialized endothelial cell localized to the leading edge of an angiogenic sprout that senses extracellular signals and guides the directed growth of blood vessels.

goterms.name: blood vessel endothelial cell migration
goterms.description: The orderly movement of an endothelial cell into the extracellular matrix in order to form new blood vessels during angiogenesis.

goterms.name: negative regulation of blood vessel endothelial cell migration
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the migration of the endothelial cells of blood vessels.

goterms.name: positive regulation of blood vessel endothelial cell migration
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the migration of the endothelial cells of blood vessels.

goterms.name: blood vessel endothelial cell fate commitment
goterms.description: The commitment of a cell to a blood vessel endothelial cell fate and its capacity to differentiate into a blood vessel endothelial cell.

goterms.name: blood vessel endothelial cell fate specification
goterms.description: The process involved in the specification of identity of a blood vessel endothelial cell. Once specification has taken place, a cell will be committed to differentiate down a specific pathway if left in its normal environment. A blood vessel endothelial cell is an endothelial cell of the vascular tree, which includes blood vessels and lymphatic vessels.

goterms.name: angiostatin binding
goterms.description: Binding to angiostatin, a proteolytic product of plasminogen or plasmin containing at least one intact kringle domain, and which is an inhibitor of angiogenesis.

goterms.name: angiogenin-PRI complex
goterms.description: A stable heterodimer of angiogenin and placental ribonuclease inhibitor; interaction between angiogenin and PRI prevents angiogenin binding to its receptor to stimulate angiogenesis.

goterms.name: alpha6-beta1 integrin-CYR61 complex
goterms.description: A protein complex that consists of an alpha6-beta1 integrin complex bound to CYR61, a cysteine-rich protein involved in angiogenesis.

goterms.name: angioblast cell migration from lateral mesoderm to midline
goterms.description: The directed movement of angioblasts from the lateral mesoderm to the midline which occurs as part of the formation of the early midline vasculature.

goterms.name: angioblast cell migration involved in selective angioblast sprouting
goterms.description: The directional migration of angioblast cells as part of selective angioblast sprouting, which results in angioblast segregation into arterial and venous populations.

goterms.name: selective angioblast sprouting
goterms.description: The segregation of angioblasts into discrete arterial and venous vessels from one common precursor vessel.

goterms.name: apoptotic process involved in blood vessel morphogenesis
goterms.description: Any apoptotic process that is involved in blood vessel morphogenesis.

goterms.name: blood vessel lumenization
goterms.description: The process in which a developing blood vessel forms an endothelial lumen through which blood will flow.

goterms.name: vasculogenesis
goterms.description: The differentiation of endothelial cells from progenitor cells during blood vessel development, and the de novo formation of blood vessels and tubes.

goterms.name: cell migration involved in vasculogenesis
goterms.description: The orderly movement of a cell from one site to another that will contribute to the differentiation of an endothelial cell that will form de novo blood vessels and tubes.

goterms.name: negative regulation of vasculogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of vasculogenesis.

goterms.name: positive regulation of vasculogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of vasculogenesis.

goterms.name: negative regulation of vasculature development
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of vasculature development.

goterms.name: negative regulation of blood vessel morphogenesis
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of blood vessel morphogenesis.

goterms.name: positive regulation of vasculature development
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of vasculature development.

goterms.name: cellular ketone body metabolic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving ketone bodies, any one of the three substances: acetoacetate, D-3-hydroxybutyrate (beta-hydroxybutyrate) or acetone, as carried out by individual cells. Although 3-hydroxybutyrate is not a ketone, it is classed as a ketone body because it exists in an equilibrium with acetoacetate. Ketone bodies may accumulate in excessive amounts in the body in starvation, diabetes mellitus or in other defects of carbohydrate metabolism.

goterms.name: ketone body biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of ketone bodies, any one of the three substances: acetoacetate, D-3-hydroxybutyrate (beta-hydroxybutyrate) or acetone. Biosynthesis involves the formation of hydroxymethylglutaryl-CoA, which is cleaved to acetate and acetyl-CoA.

goterms.name: acetoacetic acid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of acetoacetic acid, a beta-keto acid of the keto acid group, empirical formula is C4H6O3 or CH3COCH2COOH.

goterms.name: ketone body catabolic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of ketone bodies, any one of the three substances: acetoacetate, D-3-hydroxybutyrate (beta-hydroxybutyrate) or acetone. Ketone bodies can be used as an energy source as an alternative to glucose. Utilization of ketone bodies in peripheral tissues involves conversion of acetoacetate to acetoacetyl-CoA, which is then converted to two molecules of acetyl-CoA.

goterms.name: acetoacetic acid catabolic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of acetoacetic acid, a beta-keto acid of the keto acid group, empirical formula is C4H6O3 or CH3COCH2COOH.

goterms.name: insulin-like growth factor receptor signaling pathway
goterms.description: The series of molecular signals initiated by a ligand binding to an insulin-like growth factor receptor on the surface of a target cell, and ending with the regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

goterms.name: cellular response to insulin-like growth factor stimulus
goterms.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an insulin-like growth factor stimulus.

goterms.name: insulin-like growth factor I binding
goterms.description: Binding to insulin-like growth factor I.

goterms.name: insulin-like growth factor II binding
goterms.description: Binding to insulin-like growth factor II.

goterms.name: glucose import in response to insulin stimulus
goterms.description: The directed movement of the hexose monosaccharide glucose into a cell as a result of an insulin stimulus.

goterms.name: insulin receptor binding
goterms.description: Binding to an insulin receptor.

goterms.name: insulin-like growth factor receptor binding
goterms.description: Binding to an insulin-like growth factor receptor.

goterms.name: positive regulation of insulin receptor signaling pathway
goterms.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of insulin receptor signaling.

goterms.name: negative regulation of insulin receptor signaling pathway
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of insulin receptor signaling.

goterms.name: positive regulation of insulin secretion
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of insulin.

goterms.name: negative regulation of insulin secretion
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of insulin.

goterms.name: insulin-responsive glucose:proton symporter activity
goterms.description: Enables the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction: glucose(out) + H(out)+ = glucose(in) + H(in)+, in response to a stimulus by insulin. Symporter activity enables the active transport of a solute across a membrane by a mechanism whereby two or more species are transported together in the same direction in a tightly coupled process not directly linked to a form of energy other than chemiosmotic energy.

goterms.name: insulin control element activator complex
goterms.description: Transcription factor complex that binds to the insulin control element (ICE), a DNA sequence element found within the 5'-flanking region of the insulin gene, and activates ICE-mediated transcription.

goterms.name: positive regulation of cellular response to insulin stimulus
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cellular response to insulin stimulus.

goterms.name: negative regulation of cellular response to insulin stimulus
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cellular response to insulin stimulus.

goterms.name: insulin-like growth factor binding
goterms.description: Binding to an insulin-like growth factor, any member of a group of polypeptides that are structurally homologous to insulin and share many of its biological activities, but are immunologically distinct from it.

goterms.name: insulin receptor activity
goterms.description: Combining with insulin receptor ligand and transmitting the signal across the plasma membrane to initiate a change in cell activity.

goterms.name: insulin-like growth factor receptor activity
goterms.description: Combining with insulin-like growth factor receptor ligand and transmitting the signal across the plasma membrane to initiate a change in cell activity.

goterms.name: insulin processing
goterms.description: The formation of mature insulin by proteolysis of the precursor preproinsulin. The signal sequence is first cleaved from preproinsulin to form proinsulin; proinsulin is then cleaved to release the C peptide, leaving the A and B chains of mature insulin linked by disulfide bridges.

goterms.name: insulin secretion
goterms.description: The regulated release of proinsulin from secretory granules accompanied by cleavage of proinsulin to form mature insulin. In vertebrates, insulin is secreted from B granules in the B cells of the vertebrate pancreas and from insulin-producing cells in insects.

goterms.name: insulin receptor complex
goterms.description: A disulfide-bonded, heterotetrameric receptor complex. The alpha chains are entirely extracellular, while each beta chain has one transmembrane domain. The ligand binds to the alpha subunit extracellular domain and the kinase is associated with the beta subunit intracellular domain.

goterms.name: insulin-like growth factor ternary complex
goterms.description: A complex of three proteins, which in animals is approximately 150kDa and consists of the insulin-like growth factor (IGF), the insulin-like growth factor binding protein-3 (IGFBP-3), or -5 (IGFBP-5) and an acid-labile subunit (ALS). The complex plays a role in growth and development.

goterms.name: insulin-like growth factor binary complex
goterms.description: A complex of two proteins, which in animals is 50kDa and consists of the insulin-like growth factor (IGF) and one of the insulin-like growth factor binding protein-1 (IGFBP-1), -2 (IGFBP-2), -4 (IGFBP-4) and -6 (IGFBP-6). The complex plays a role in growth and development.

goterms.name: insulin-like growth factor binding protein complex
goterms.description: A complex of proteins which includes the insulin-like growth factor (IGF) and a number of IGF-binding proteins. The complex plays a role in growth and development.

goterms.name: insulin catabolic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of insulin.

goterms.name: insulin metabolic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving insulin.

goterms.name: insulin binding
goterms.description: Binding to insulin, a polypeptide hormone produced by the islets of Langerhans of the pancreas in mammals, and by the homologous organs of other organisms.

goterms.name: negative regulation of insulin-like growth factor receptor signaling pathway
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of insulin-like growth factor receptor signaling.

goterms.name: positive regulation of insulin-like growth factor receptor signaling pathway
goterms.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of insulin-like growth factor receptor signaling.

goterms.name: insulin receptor substrate binding
goterms.description: Binding to an insulin receptor substrate (IRS) protein, an adaptor protein that bind to the transphosphorylated insulin and insulin-like growth factor receptors, are themselves phosphorylated and in turn recruit SH2 domain-containing signaling molecules to form a productive signaling complex.

goterms.name: response to insulin-like growth factor stimulus
goterms.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an insulin-like growth factor stimulus.

goterms.name: negative regulation of insulin secretion involved in cellular response to glucose stimulus
goterms.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of insulin that contributes to the response of a cell to glucose.

goterms.name: insulin receptor recycling
goterms.description: The process that results in the return of an insulin receptor to an active state at the plasma membrane. An active state is when the receptor is ready to receive an insulin signal. Internalized insulin receptors can be recycled to the plasma membrane or sorted to lysosomes for protein degradation.

goterms.name: insulin receptor signaling pathway via phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase
goterms.description: An insulin receptor signaling pathway in which the signal is transmitted via the phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase cascade.

goterms.name: insulin receptor internalization
goterms.description: A receptor-mediated endocytosis process that results in the movement of an insulin receptor from the plasma membrane to the inside of the cell.

goterms.name: positive regulation of insulin receptor signaling pathway by insulin receptor internalization
goterms.description: Any process in which internalization of an insulin receptor activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the insulin receptor signaling pathway. Endocytosis of activated receptors can concentrate receptors within endosomes and allow the insulin receptor to phosphorylate substrates that are spatially distinct from those accessible at the plasma membrane.

goterms.name: negative regulation of insulin receptor signaling pathway by insulin receptor internalization
goterms.description: Any process in which internalization of an insulin receptor stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of insulin receptor signal transduction. Internalization of insulin in association with its receptor clears insulin from the circulation and is necessary for subsequent insulin dissociation from the receptor and insulin degradation.

goterms.name: positive regulation of insulin secretion involved in cellular response to glucose stimulus
goterms.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of insulin that contributes to the response of a cell to glucose.

goterms.name: insulin secretion involved in cellular response to glucose stimulus
goterms.description: The regulated release of proinsulin from secretory granules (B granules) in the B cells of the pancreas; accompanied by cleavage of proinsulin to form mature insulin, in response to a glucose stimulus.

goterms.name: cellular response to insulin stimulus
goterms.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an insulin stimulus. Insulin is a polypeptide hormone produced by the islets of Langerhans of the pancreas in mammals, and by the homologous organs of other organisms.

goterms.name: response to insulin
goterms.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an insulin stimulus. Insulin is a polypeptide hormone produced by the islets of Langerhans of the pancreas in mammals, and by the homologous organs of other organisms.

goterms.name: insulin-responsive compartment
goterms.description: A small membrane-bounded vesicle that releases its contents by exocytosis in response to insulin stimulation; the contents are enriched in GLUT4, IRAP and VAMP2.

goterms.name: insulin receptor signaling pathway
goterms.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of the insulin receptor binding to insulin.

goterms.name: type B pancreatic cell proliferation
goterms.description: The multiplication or reproduction of pancreatic B cells, resulting in the expansion of an pancreatic B cell population. Pancreatic B cell are cells of the pancreas that secrete insulin.

goterms.name: canonical Wnt signaling pathway involved in regulation of type B pancreatic cell proliferation
goterms.description: The series of molecular signals initiated by binding of a Wnt protein to a frizzled family receptor on the surface of the target cell, followed by propagation of the signal via beta-catenin, and ending with a change in transcription of target genes that modulates the rate or frequency of pancreatic B cell proliferation. Pancreatic B cell are cells of the pancreas that secrete insulin.

goterms.name: type B pancreatic cell differentiation
goterms.description: The process in which relatively unspecialized cells acquire specialized structural and/or functional features of a type B pancreatic cell. A type B pancreatic cell is a cell located towards center of the islets of Langerhans that secretes insulin.

goterms.name: type B pancreatic cell development
goterms.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a type B pancreatic cell over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A type B pancreatic cell is a cell located towards center of the islets of Langerhans that secretes insulin.

goterms.name: type B pancreatic cell fate commitment
goterms.description: The commitment of a cell to a type B pancreatic cell fate and its capacity to differentiate into a type B pancreatic cell. A type B pancreatic cell is a cell located towards center of the islets of Langerhans that secretes insulin.

goterms.name: type B pancreatic cell apoptotic process
goterms.description: Any apoptotic process in a type B pancreatic cell, a cell located towards center of the islets of Langerhans that secretes insulin.

goterms.name: alphav-beta3 integrin-IGF-1-IGF1R complex
goterms.description: A protein complex that consists of an alphav-beta3 integrin complex bound to insulin-like growth factor-1 (IGF-1) and type I insulin-like growth factor receptor (IGF1R). IGF1R is a heterotetramer that consists of two alpha-subunits and two beta-subunits.

goterms.name: endocrine pancreas development
goterms.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the endocrine pancreas over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The endocrine pancreas is made up of islet cells that produce insulin, glucagon and somatostatin.

goterms.name: type B pancreatic cell maturation
goterms.description: A developmental process, independent of morphogenetic (shape) change, that is required for a type B pancreatic cell to attain its fully functional state. A type B pancreatic cell is a cell located towards center of the islets of Langerhans that secretes insulin.

goterms.name: glucose transmembrane transport
goterms.description: The process in which glucose is transported across a membrane.

goterms.name: glucose import
goterms.description: The directed movement of the hexose monosaccharide glucose into a cell or organelle.

goterms.name: glucose import across plasma membrane
goterms.description: The directed movement of glucose from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

goterms.name: glucose transmembrane transporter activity
goterms.description: Enables the transfer of the hexose monosaccharide glucose from one side of a membrane to the other.

goterms.name: negative regulation of glucose transmembrane transport
goterms.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of glucose transport across a membrane. Glucose transport is the directed movement of the hexose monosaccharide glucose into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

goterms.name: positive regulation of glucose transmembrane transport
goterms.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of glucose transport across a membrane. Glucose transport is the directed movement of the hexose monosaccharide glucose into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

goterms.name: negative regulation of glucose import
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the import of the hexose monosaccharide glucose into a cell or organelle.

goterms.name: positive regulation of glucose import
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the import of the hexose monosaccharide glucose into a cell or organelle.

goterms.name: glucose uniporter activity
goterms.description: Enables the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction: glucose(out) = glucose(in).

goterms.name: glucose-6-phosphate transmembrane transporter activity
goterms.description: Enables the transfer of glucose-6-phosphate from one side of a membrane to the other. Glucose-6-phosphate is a monophosphorylated derivative of glucose with the phosphate group attached to C-6.

goterms.name: glucose 6-phosphate:inorganic phosphate antiporter activity
goterms.description: Enables the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction: glucose 6-phosphate(out) + inorganic phosphate(in) = glucose 6-phosphate(in) + inorganic phosphate(out).

goterms.name: intracellular glucose homeostasis
goterms.description: A homeostatic process involved in the maintenance of a steady state level of glucose within a cell.

goterms.name: cellular response to glucose stimulus
goterms.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a glucose stimulus.

goterms.name: glucose homeostasis
goterms.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of glucose within an organism or cell.

goterms.name: glucose transporter complex
goterms.description: A protein complex facilitating glucose transport into, out of or within a cell, or between cells.

goterms.name: positive regulation of glucose mediated signaling pathway
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of glucose mediated signaling pathway.

goterms.name: negative regulation of glucose mediated signaling pathway
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of glucose mediated signaling pathway.

goterms.name: regulation of adenylate cyclase-activating glucose-activated G protein-coupled receptor signaling pathway
goterms.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the adenylate cyclase-activating glucose-activated G protein-coupled receptor signaling pathway, the series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of glucose binding to a G protein-coupled receptor, where the pathway proceeds with activation of adenylyl cyclase and a subsequent increase in the concentration of cyclic AMP (cAMP).

goterms.name: regulation of transcription by glucose
goterms.description: Any process involving glucose that modulates the frequency, rate or extent or transcription.

goterms.name: negative regulation of transcription by glucose
goterms.description: Any process involving glucose that decreases the frequency, rate or extent or transcription.

goterms.name: positive regulation of transcription by glucose
goterms.description: Any process involving glucose that activates or increases the rate of transcription.

goterms.name: eNoSc complex
goterms.description: A chromatin silencing complex that recruits histone-modifying enzymes and upregulates silencing of rDNA in response to glucose starvation.

goterms.name: response to glucose
goterms.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a glucose stimulus.

goterms.name: detection of glucose
goterms.description: The series of events in which a glucose stimulus is received by a cell and converted into a molecular signal.

goterms.name: negative regulation of detection of glucose
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of detection of glucose.

goterms.name: positive regulation of detection of glucose
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of detection of glucose.

goterms.name: cellular response to starvation
goterms.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of deprivation of nourishment.

goterms.name: cellular response to glucose starvation
goterms.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of deprivation of glucose.

goterms.name: positive regulation of protein export from nucleus in response to glucose starvation
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of directed movement of proteins from the nucleus into the cytoplasm in response to deprivation of glucose.

goterms.name: positive regulation of transcription from RNA polymerase II promoter in response to glucose starvation
goterms.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of transcription from an RNA polymerase II promoter as a result of deprivation of glucose.

goterms.name: T cell activation
goterms.description: The change in morphology and behavior of a mature or immature T cell resulting from exposure to a mitogen, cytokine, chemokine, cellular ligand, or an antigen for which it is specific.

goterms.name: negative regulation of T cell activation
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of T cell activation.

goterms.name: positive regulation of T cell activation
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of T cell activation.

goterms.name: T cell activation involved in immune response
goterms.description: The change in morphology and behavior of a mature or immature T cell resulting from exposure to a mitogen, cytokine, chemokine, cellular ligand, or an antigen for which it is specific, leading to the initiation or perpetuation of an immune response.

goterms.name: T-helper 17 type immune response
goterms.description: An immune response which is associated with resistance to intracellular bacteria with a key role in inflammation and tissue injury. This immune response is associated with pathological autoimmune conditions such as multiple sclerosis, arthritis and psoriasis which is typically orchestrated by the production of particular cytokines by T-helper 17 cells, most notably interleukin-17, IL-21 and IL-22.

goterms.name: negative regulation of T-helper 17 type immune response
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of T-helper 17 type immune response.

goterms.name: positive regulation of T-helper 17 type immune response
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of T-helper 17 type immune response.

goterms.name: lipid storage
goterms.description: The accumulation and maintenance in cells or tissues of lipids, compounds soluble in organic solvents but insoluble or sparingly soluble in aqueous solvents. Lipid reserves can be accumulated during early developmental stages for mobilization and utilization at later stages of development.

goterms.name: cholesterol storage
goterms.description: The accumulation and maintenance in cells or tissues of cholesterol, cholest-5-en-3 beta-ol, the principal sterol of vertebrates and the precursor of many steroids, including bile acids and steroid hormones.

goterms.name: lipid droplet formation
goterms.description: A process that results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts of a lipid droplet.

goterms.name: positive regulation of lipid storage
goterms.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of lipid storage. Lipid storage is the accumulation and maintenance in cells or tissues of lipids, compounds soluble in organic solvents but insoluble or sparingly soluble in aqueous solvents. Lipid reserves can be accumulated during early developmental stages for mobilization and utilization at later stages of development.

goterms.name: negative regulation of lipid storage
goterms.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of lipid storage. Lipid storage is the accumulation and maintenance in cells or tissues of lipids, compounds soluble in organic solvents but insoluble or sparingly soluble in aqueous solvents. Lipid reserves can be accumulated during early developmental stages for mobilization and utilization at later stages of development.

goterms.name: sequestering of triglyceride
goterms.description: The process of binding or confining any triester of glycerol such that it is separated from other components of a biological system.

goterms.name: negative regulation of sequestering of triglyceride
goterms.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of sequestering of triglyceride. Triglyceride sequestration is the process of binding or confining any triester of glycerol such that it is separated from other components of a biological system.

goterms.name: positive regulation of sequestering of triglyceride
goterms.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of sequestering of triglyceride. Triglyceride sequestration is the process of binding or confining any triester of glycerol such that it is separated from other components of a biological system.

goterms.name: cholesterol transport involved in cholesterol storage
goterms.description: The directed movement of cholesterol into cells that is part of their accumulation and maintenance.

goterms.name: negative regulation of cholesterol storage
goterms.description: Any process that decreases the rate or extent of cholesterol storage. Cholesterol storage is the accumulation and maintenance in cells or tissues of cholesterol, cholest-5-en-3 beta-ol, the principal sterol of vertebrates and the precursor of many steroids, including bile acids and steroid hormones.

goterms.name: positive regulation of cholesterol storage
goterms.description: Any process that increases the rate or extent of cholesterol storage. Cholesterol storage is the accumulation and maintenance in cells or tissues of cholesterol, cholest-5-en-3 beta-ol, the principal sterol of vertebrates and the precursor of many steroids, including bile acids and steroid hormones.

goterms.name: adipose tissue development
goterms.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of adipose tissue over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Adipose tissue is specialized tissue that is used to store fat.

goterms.name: fat pad development
goterms.description: The progression of a fat pad from its initial formation to its mature structure. A fat pad is an accumulation of adipose tissue.

goterms.name: mammary gland fat development
goterms.description: The progression of the mammary gland fat over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The mammary fat is an adipose structure in the gland that is invaded by the mammary ducts.

goterms.name: negative regulation of adipose tissue development
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of adipose tissue development.

goterms.name: positive regulation of adipose tissue development
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of adipose tissue development.

goterms.name: fat cell apoptotic process
goterms.description: Any apoptotic process in a fat cell.

goterms.name: negative regulation of fat cell apoptotic process
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of fat cell apoptotic process.

goterms.name: positive regulation of fat cell apoptotic process
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of fat cell apoptotic process.

goterms.name: lipid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of lipids, compounds soluble in an organic solvent but not, or sparingly, in an aqueous solvent.

goterms.name: cellular lipid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of lipids, as carried out by individual cells.

goterms.name: emericellamide biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of emericellamide.

goterms.name: fatty acid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a fatty acid, any of the aliphatic monocarboxylic acids that can be liberated by hydrolysis from naturally occurring fats and oils. Fatty acids are predominantly straight-chain acids of 4 to 24 carbon atoms, which may be saturated or unsaturated; branched fatty acids and hydroxy fatty acids also occur, and very long chain acids of over 30 carbons are found in waxes.

goterms.name: fatty acid derivative biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of fatty acid derivative.

goterms.name: negative regulation of lipid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of lipids.

goterms.name: neutral lipid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of neutral lipids, lipids only soluble in solvents of very low polarity.

goterms.name: positive regulation of lipid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of lipids.

goterms.name: steroid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of steroids, compounds with a 1,2,cyclopentanoperhydrophenanthrene nucleus; includes de novo formation and steroid interconversion by modification.

goterms.name: acyl carrier activity
goterms.description: Binding an acyl group and presenting it for processing or offloading to a cognate enzyme. Covalently binds the acyl group via a phosphopantetheine prosthetic group and mediates protein-protein interactions with the enzyme conferring specificity. The acyl carrier protein (ACP) presents substrates to enzymes involved in fatty acid biosynthesis or in polyketide secondary metabolite biosynthesis.

goterms.name: fatty acid elongation
goterms.description: The elongation of a fatty acid chain by the sequential addition of two-carbon units.

goterms.name: butyryl-CoA biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathway resulting in the formation of butyryl-CoA.

goterms.name: long-chain fatty acid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a long-chain fatty acid, a fatty acid with an aliphatic tail of 13 to 21 carbons.

goterms.name: lipoate biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of lipoate, 1,2-dithiolane-3-pentanoate, the anion derived from lipoic acid.

goterms.name: medium-chain fatty acid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a fatty acid with an aliphatic tail of 6 to 12 carbons.

goterms.name: methionine catabolic process to 3-methylthiopropanoate
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving the catabolism of amino acids to produce carboxylic acids with one carbon less than the starting amino acid. In S. cerevisiae, this is known to occur for leucine, isoleucine, valine, methionine, phenylalanine, tyrosine, or tryptophan. When methionine is used as the substrate, 3-methylthiopropanoate is produced. Often referred to as the Ehrlich pathway, these reactions generally occur during fermentation to produce a variety of carboxylic acids, sometimes collectively referred to as fusel acids. Depending on the redox state of the cells, alcohol derivatives may be produced instead of carboxylic acids.

goterms.name: methyl-branched fatty acid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of methyl-branched fatty acid.

goterms.name: monounsaturated fatty acid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of monounsaturated fatty acid.

goterms.name: mycolic acid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of mycolic acids, beta-hydroxy fatty acids with a long alpha-alkyl side chain.

goterms.name: negative regulation of fatty acid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of fatty acids.

goterms.name: positive regulation of fatty acid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of fatty acids.

goterms.name: short-chain fatty acid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a fatty acid with an aliphatic tail of less than 6 carbons.

goterms.name: unsaturated fatty acid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of an unsaturated fatty acid, any fatty acid containing one or more double bonds between carbon atoms.

goterms.name: very long-chain fatty acid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a very long chain fatty acid, a fatty acid with an aliphatic tail of 22 or more carbons.

goterms.name: negative regulation of butyryl-CoA biosynthetic process from acetyl-CoA
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of butyryl-CoA biosynthetic process from acetyl-CoA.

goterms.name: positive regulation of butyryl-CoA biosynthetic process from acetyl-CoA
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of butyryl-CoA biosynthetic process from acetyl-CoA.

goterms.name: negative regulation of butyryl-CoA catabolic process to butyrate
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of butyryl-CoA catabolic process to butyrate.

goterms.name: positive regulation of butyryl-CoA catabolic process to butyrate
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of butyryl-CoA catabolic process to butyrate.

goterms.name: positive regulation of unsaturated fatty acid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of unsaturated fatty acid biosynthetic process.

goterms.name: lipid transport
goterms.description: The directed movement of lipids into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. Lipids are compounds soluble in an organic solvent but not, or sparingly, in an aqueous solvent.

goterms.name: fatty acid derivative transport
goterms.description: The directed movement of a fatty acid derivative into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

goterms.name: fatty acid transport
goterms.description: The directed movement of fatty acids into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. Fatty acids are aliphatic monocarboxylic acids liberated from naturally occurring fats and oils by hydrolysis.

goterms.name: lipid export from cell
goterms.description: The directed movement of a lipid from a cell, into the extracellular region.

goterms.name: lipid import into cell
goterms.description: The directed movement of a lipid from outside of a cell into a cell. This may occur via transport across the plasma membrane or via endocytosis.

goterms.name: lipid translocation
goterms.description: The translocation, or flipping, of lipid molecules from one monolayer of a membrane bilayer to the opposite monolayer.

goterms.name: lipid transport involved in lipid storage
goterms.description: The directed movement of lipids into cells that is part of their accumulation and maintenance.

goterms.name: negative regulation of lipid transport
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of lipids into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

goterms.name: positive regulation of lipid transport
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of lipids into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

goterms.name: negative regulation of fatty acid transport
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of fatty acid transport.

goterms.name: positive regulation of fatty acid transport
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of fatty acid transport.

goterms.name: negative regulation of long-chain fatty acid import into cell
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of long-chain fatty acid import into a cell.

goterms.name: positive regulation of long-chain fatty acid import into cell
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of long-chain fatty acid import into a cell.

goterms.name: triglyceride biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a triglyceride, any triester of glycerol.

goterms.name: negative regulation of triglyceride biosynthetic process
goterms.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, or extent of triglyceride biosynthesis. Triglyceride biosynthesis is the collection of chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of triglyceride, any triester of glycerol.

goterms.name: positive regulation of triglyceride biosynthetic process
goterms.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of triglyceride biosynthesis. Triglyceride biosynthesis is the collection of chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of triglyceride, any triester of glycerol.

goterms.name: glycerol biosynthetic process from pyruvate
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of glycerol, 1,2,3-propanetriol, from other compounds, including pyruvate.

goterms.name: positive regulation of receptor-mediated endocytosis involved in cholesterol transport
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of receptor-mediated endocytosis involved in cholesterol transport.

goterms.name: negative regulation of receptor-mediated endocytosis involved in cholesterol transport
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of receptor-mediated endocytosis involved in cholesterol transport.

goterms.name: receptor-mediated endocytosis involved in cholesterol transport
goterms.description: A receptor-mediated endocytosis process involved in intracellular cholesterol transport.

goterms.name: cholesterol ester hydrolysis involved in cholesterol transport
goterms.description: The cholesterol metabolic process in which cholesterol esters are hydrolyzed into free fatty acids and cholesterol in the lysosome that contributes to intracellular cholesterol transport.

goterms.name: lysosome to ER cholesterol transport
goterms.description: The directed movement of cholesterol, cholest-5-en-3-beta-ol, or cholesterol-containing compounds, from the lysosome to the endoplasmic reticulum.

goterms.name: negative regulation of cholesterol efflux
goterms.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of cholesterol efflux. Cholesterol efflux is the directed movement of cholesterol, cholest-5-en-3-beta-ol, out of a cell or organelle.

goterms.name: positive regulation of cholesterol efflux
goterms.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of cholesterol efflux. Cholesterol efflux is the directed movement of cholesterol, cholest-5-en-3-beta-ol, out of a cell or organelle.
cholesterol efflux

goterms.name: positive regulation of cholesterol import
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cholesterol import.

goterms.name: negative regulation of cholesterol import
goterms.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of cholesterol import. Cholesterol import is the directed movement of cholesterol into a cell or organelle.

goterms.name: cholesterol import
goterms.description: The directed movement of cholesterol into a cell or organelle.

goterms.name: negative regulation of cholesterol biosynthetic process
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of cholesterol.

goterms.name: positive regulation of cholesterol biosynthetic process
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of cholesterol.

goterms.name: negative regulation of cholesterol transporter activity
goterms.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, or extent of cholesterol transporter activity.

goterms.name: cholesterol biosynthetic process via lathosterol
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of cholesterol, cholest-5-en-3 beta-ol, via the intermediate lathosterol.

goterms.name: cholesterol biosynthetic process via 24,25-dihydrolanosterol
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of cholesterol, cholest-5-en-3 beta-ol, via the intermediate 24,25-dihydrolanosterol.

goterms.name: cholesterol biosynthetic process via desmosterol
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of cholesterol, cholest-5-en-3 beta-ol, via the intermediate desmosterol.
cholesterol catabolic process

goterms.name: lipid droplet disassembly
goterms.description: The disaggregation of a lipid particle into its constituent components.

goterms.name: membrane lipid catabolic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of membrane lipids, any lipid found in or associated with a biological membrane.

goterms.name: membrane lipid biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of membrane lipids, any lipid found in or associated with a biological membrane.

goterms.name: cellular lipid catabolic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of lipids, as carried out by individual cells.

goterms.name: lipid catabolic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of lipids, compounds soluble in an organic solvent but not, or sparingly, in an aqueous solvent.

goterms.name: positive regulation of lipid catabolic process
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of lipids.

goterms.name: negative regulation of lipid catabolic process
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of lipids.

goterms.name: lipid digestion
goterms.description: The whole of the physical, chemical, and biochemical processes carried out by living organisms to break down ingested lipids into components that may be easily absorbed and directed into metabolism.

goterms.name: lipid ubiquitination
goterms.description: The process in which one or more ubiquitin groups are added to a lipid.

goterms.name: myo-inositol hexakisphosphate biosynthetic process, lipid-dependent
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of 1D-myo-inositol 1,2,3,4,5,6-hexakisphosphate, phytate, by a pathway using inositol 1,4,5-trisphosphate produced from phosphatidylinositol 4,5-biphosphate hydrolysis by phospholipase C.

goterms.name: negative regulation of lipase activity
goterms.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of lipase activity, the hydrolysis of a lipid or phospholipid.

goterms.name: positive regulation of lipase activity
goterms.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of lipase activity, the hydrolysis of a lipid or phospholipid.

goterms.name: lipophagy
goterms.description: The selective autophagy process in which lipid droplets are delivered to the vacuole and degraded in response to changing cellular conditions.

goterms.name: ubiquinone catabolic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of ubiquinone, a lipid-soluble electron-transporting coenzyme.

goterms.name: glycerol biosynthetic process
goterms.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of glycerol, 1,2,3-propanetriol, a sweet, hygroscopic, viscous liquid, widely distributed in nature as a constituent of many lipids.

goterms.name: white fat cell differentiation
goterms.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a white adipocyte, an animal connective tissue cell involved in energy storage. White adipocytes have cytoplasmic lipids arranged in a unique vacuole.

goterms.name: white fat cell proliferation
goterms.description: The multiplication or reproduction of white fat cells by cell division, resulting in the expansion of their population.

goterms.name: positive regulation of white fat cell proliferation
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of white fat cell proliferation.

goterms.name: negative regulation of white fat cell proliferation
goterms.description: Any process that stops or decreases the rate or extent of white fat cell proliferation.

goterms.name: fat cell differentiation
goterms.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of an adipocyte, an animal connective tissue cell specialized for the synthesis and storage of fat.

goterms.name: fat cell proliferation
goterms.description: The multiplication or reproduction of fat cells by cell division, resulting in the expansion of their population. A fat cell is an animal connective tissue cell specialized for the synthesis and storage of fat.

goterms.name: positive regulation of fat cell differentiation
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of adipocyte differentiation.

goterms.name: negative regulation of fat cell differentiation
goterms.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of adipocyte differentiation.

goterms.name: positive regulation of fat cell proliferation
goterms.description: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of fat cell proliferation.

goterms.name: negative regulation of fat cell proliferation
goterms.description: Any process that stops or decreases the rate or extent of fat cell proliferation.

goterms.name: leptin receptor activity
goterms.description: Combining with the fat-cell specific hormone leptin and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.
